 costing the average £160,000 for the region, a buyer would save £1,600 under the change.</p><p></p><p>The Welsh Conservatives said there would be more details in their manifesto for the 2016 assembly election.</p><p></p><p>Andrew RT Davies, leader of the party, told BBC Radio Wales: \"If you ask most people what their dream is, it is to own their own property. And one of the things that proves to be the biggest obstacle is the final couple of pounds people need to put in place to secure that property. And stamp duty is one of the equations you have to jump through to secure the deal.\"</p><p></p><p>Housing expert Henry Pryor said it was a purely political move to win favour among locals, and was unlikely to see a flood of English buyers moving to Wales. \"The average house price in Wales is 10% below the average in the West Midlands, so it's already a lot cheaper to buy there – an extra 1% isn't going to make a difference and encrouage buyers to move to Wales,\" he said.</p><p></p><p>Nick Barnes, head of research at estate agent Chesterton Humberts, agreed: \"It is likely to benefit first-time buyers, although I suppose it could attract the attention of investors picking up property in big cities such as Swansea and Cardiff where there is a decent-sized population. But it'll be interesting to see if the party actually carry out what they've promised.\"</p><p></p><p>Stamp duty is zero for property sold up to the £125,000 mark; between £125,000 and £250,000 it is 1%; and between £250,000 and £500,000 it is 3%, rising to 4% for properties costing £500,000 to £1m.</p><p></p><p>The Conservatives said they would continue to levy stamp duty at 3% on properties sold for more than £250,000.</p>","headline":"Lowest stamp duty bracket will be axed, say Welsh Conservatives","trailText":"Removal of levy of 1% on homes sold for between £125,000 and £250,000 will help first-time buyers on to ladder, party says","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRe