e \"very serious\".</p><p>The regulator said callers were kept hanging on the line, unaware in many cases that it was costing them £2.39 a minute, and many of the victims were elderly or vulnerable – those least likely to have access to the internet where <a href=\"http://www.thephonebook.bt.com/publisha.content/en/search/residential/search.publisha\" title=\"\">phone numbers are freely available</a>.</p><p>One customer ran up an £81 bill, while another seems to have been charged £454 in three months.</p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.phonepayplus.org.uk/For-Business/Adjudications/2014/1/BRITISH-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-PLC-27976-Track-2-FD30F10A-4C63-E311-8A98-4EFAAEEBB3B0.aspx\" title=\"\">tribunal decision was made in January</a>, but has only just come to light. Customers who were overcharged need to apply to BT for a refund.</p><p>Guardian Money has long warned of the absurd cost of calling the various directory services now on offer.</p><p>The BT service carries a connection charge of 59p for the first minute, then subsequently charges £2.39 a minute. Callers must often listen to long automated messages before their request is dealt with, meaning they almost inevitably start incurring the higher rate.</p><p>Staff then ask callers if they want to be put through to the number they requested, rather than dial it themselves, which means they pay £2.39 a minute for the rest of the call.</p><p>The cost of ringing directory enquiries has spiralled since the system was opened up to competition in 2003, when the BT 192 directory enquiries service charged a flat fee of 40p a call.</p><p>PhonepayPlus said the majority of complainants stated that pricing was not shown in the promotional material, or that the pricing information was incorrect. It said some consumers experienced \"bill shock\" whereby the cost was hugely different to that expected.</p><p>It also said BT must refund all consumers who claim a refund, for the full amount spent by them on the service, within 28 days of their claim, unless there is good cause to believe that such claims are not valid.</p><p>A spokeswoman for BT said it had never intended to rip customers off and accepted it should have made the call cost clearer on its phone books. However, it denied other breaches of the industry code of practice.</p><p>\"BT apologises for the breaches, which were due to oversights and different interpretations of the code rather than any attempt to mislead customers,\" the spokeswoman said. \"We feel the pricing information on the website was correctly placed so as not to confuse customers and, while the customer message we previously used was a few seconds longer than the guidance recommends, customers tell us they found it helpful.\"</p><p>She said the company had already introduced a shorter message and refunded individual customers where they felt they had not had the \"full information\".</p><p>PhonepayPlus said any customers who have been unfairly denied a refund should contact them.</p>","headline":"BT to refund directory enquiries customers after failings lead to £81 call","trailText":"<p>Premium rate number watchdog describes the firm's failings as 'serious', with customers unaware they were being charged £2.39 a minute</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mea6","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/4/1391514627562/BT-logo-006.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/4/1391514627562/BT-logo-006.jpg","wordcount":"507","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"428874875","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8643004","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Miles Brignall","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-04T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2037831","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-07T12:15:00Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":tr