m a year.</p><p>\"There are significant concerns that under the current regime, Ofcom's decisions can be derailed too easily, through technical challenges that ignore the substance of the regulator's judgments,\" the letter states. \"The routine use of legal challenges has had a chilling effect on policy. It diverts time and money into legal disputes and away from good regulation. This is bad news for competition, for the industry, and for consumers.\"</p><p>For example, seven years after Ofcom first proposed a consumer-friendly switching system, UK consumers do not benefit from the same freedom to change service providers as other Europeans.</p><p>A decision on whether to proceed with reforming the appeals process is expected shortly from Miller. Lobbying has already succeeded in narrowing the scope of reform. When <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2012/dec/06/regulators-lawyers-ofcom\" title=\"\">the changes were announced</a> in the Chancellor's 2012 Autumn statement, they were intended to cover all regulators, including Ofgem for electricity and gas, Ofwat for water and sewerage, the Civil Aviation Authority and the Office of Rail Regulation.</p><p>It is understood the changes will now be restricted to Ofcom, which covers media, telecoms and postal services.</p><p>The larger operators, Vodafone, BT, Sky and EE, argue that changing the regime may cause problems in cases where regulators have made mistakes.</p><p>But Ofcom has been particularly vocal about the need for change. Its chief executive, Ed Richards, said earlier this year that the UK system was \"too legalistic and too open to gaming\" by companies able to pay for large legal teams, and that \"everything we do now is subject to the huge shadow of threat of litigation\".</p><p>Ofcom's battle to loosen Sky's grip on film and sports broadcasting, which had seen the issue pass to the Competition Appeal Tribunal and eventually the Competition Commission, took five years and ended in a defeat for the regulator.</p><p>The latest round of cuts to the cost of calling a mobile was blocked for 14 months by legal challenges from network operators before being approved on appeal earlier this year.</p><p>And a move to allow consumers to transfer their mobile number from one network to another in a matter of hours rather than days has been held up since 2007, following a 2008 legal challenge by Vodafone.</p>","headline":"'Ofcom's decisons too easily derailed by companies it regulates'","trailText":"Consumer organisations – and two companies – point to the chilling of consumer rights due to expensive technical appeals","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3meqt","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/4/1391548459902/Ofcoms-building-006.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/4/1391548459902/Ofcoms-building-006.jpg","wordcount":"494","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"428922531","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8645999","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Juliette Garside","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-05T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2038275","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-08T07:00:09Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/05/ofcom-decisions-too-easily-derailed-companies","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/media/2014/feb/05/ofcom-decisions-too-easily-derailed-companies","tags":[{"id":"media/ofcom","webTitle":"Ofcom","type":"keyword","sectionId":"media","sectionName":"Media","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/media/ofcom","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/media/ofcom","references":[]},{"id":"media/television","webTitle":"Television industry","type":"keyword","sectionId":"media","sectionName":"Media","webUrl":"http://www