urther arguments regarding bills.</p><p>My ex put down a deposit of around £8,000 for the house and we agreed I would buy various items of furniture and household equipment while she was saving this up. During the time we were together in the house we never worried about who was paying for what as we thought of everything as one. The direct debit for the mortgage comes out of my current account.</p><p>Until recently, she paid her half of council tax, mortgage and other bills. However, a couple of weeks ago she said to me that she will no longer pay anything as she put down all the deposit, and she doesn't see why she should pay any of the mortgage or other bills any more.</p><p>The house has been on the market for eight weeks now. What would be my best course of action? Should I:</p><p>• Keep on paying the council tax, bills and the mortgage on my own and hope/try to get back what would be owed to me when we sell the house</p><p>• Stop paying the mortgage and wait for the property to be repossessed (I know it's not the best option)</p><p>• Pay only half of the mortgage?</p><p>If I carry on paying everything, what chance do I have of getting back from her what she owes me, and how would I go about it? If she wants to buy me out do I have to support any solicitor fees or other fees, or would it be solely her responsibility? If I take her to court because she is refusing to pay what I mentioned above, who would cover the court fees? <strong>SN</strong></p><p><strong>A</strong> While taking your ex-girlfriend to court in order to agree your financial matters might help her to focus on how you will share out your money and possessions, going to court isn't necessarily the best answer. What is more, before a court will consider making a decision for you it will usually require evidence that you have tried mediation. If you haven't done so, going to court will be a waste of time and you really shouldn't consider it as an option without <a href=\"http://www.resolution.org.uk/findamember\" title=\"\">first getting advice from a good family solicitor</a>. You'll also each need to see a solicitor if you and your ex agree that one of you will buy the other out. You will each pay your own solicitor.</p><p>But what you and she really need to do first is work out a fair way of dividing your money and property. If you can't manage to work things out between you (the cheapest option), you should consider using a mediator trained to help you focus on the issues that need to be resolved, which typically costs about £80 a session. More information on how to come to an agreement and using mediation is available in the <a href=\"http://www.advicenow.org.uk/living-together/breaking-up/\" title=\"\">Breaking up survival guide on the Advice Now website</a>.</p><p>What you can't do is pay only half the mortgage, because your lender is in control of the amount taken by direct debit, not you. What you definitely shouldn't do is stop paying the mortgage altogether and wait for the property to be repossessed. If you did you would incur all sorts of charges associated with repossession and run the risk that the property is sold for less than it would be worth on the open market.</p><p>Finally, it makes sense for you to carry on paying the mortgage and bills on your own for the time being, but you need to keep a record of your ex-girlfriend's share that you will have paid. How you will be repaid for this is one of the things you need to agree on with your ex, whether you choose to use the services of a mediator or not. As far as splitting your possessions goes, the law says that it belongs to you if you owned it before you got together or you bought something with your own money or you inherited something.</p>","headline":"How can my ex and I resolve a property disagreement?","trailText":"<p>She paid the deposit on our house, and now we've split up she won't pay anything towards the mortgage or bills while we attempt a sale</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","