dvocated a gospel of leisure, arguing that technology should be used to curtail work time as far as possible.' Photograph: OJO Images/Rex Features","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"How do I become … a food stylist","webPublicationDate":"2014-02-04T09:04:00Z","sectionName":"Money","sectionId":"money","id":"money/2014/feb/04/how-become-food-stylist","fields":{"standfirst":"Preparing food, washing up, sweeping floors – start low but aim high and you might find yourself styling food for the big names","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-02-04T09:50:42Z","body":"<p>\"When I tell people what I do, one of the first things they often say is, 'I bet you have to fake it quite often to make the food look better',\" says Annie Hudson, a food stylist.</p><p>Hudson's job involves preparing and presenting perfect food so it can be photographed for magazines, cookery books and advertising campaigns. \"In the past, food stylists probably had to do things like paint chickens with Bovril to make them look tastier, but, honestly, everything we do could be eaten at the end of a shoot – although it sometimes might be a bit cold.\"</p><p>Hudson came relatively late to the food industry, after a 20-year career in financial services. \"Going to cookery school was something I always really, really wanted to do, and I thought I should have done it when I first left school,\" she says. \"Once I had started to think seriously about leaving my job it took me about a year before I finally did and enrolled in a cookery school.\"</p><p>She was 42 when she began training at <a href=\"http://www.leiths.com/\" title=\"Leiths School of Food and Wine website\">Leiths School of Food and Wine</a> in London, which runs professional culinary courses for people looking for a career in food. \"It was an expensive endeavour, and not something I could have done without giving it a lot of thought and saving up for the fees. I was extremely fortunate to have the support of my husband during the course.\" She graduated with the Leiths diploma in food and wine, earning a distinction, and the advanced <a href=\"http://www.wsetglobal.com/\" title=\"WSET website\">Wine and Spirit Education Trust</a> wine certificate.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-428862020'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/3/1391441313695/Food-stylist-Annie-Hudson-001.jpg' alt='Food stylist Annie Hudson' width='220' height='292' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Food stylist Annie Hudson</figcaption></figure><p>Hudson knew the long hours of a top kitchen would not suit her, and thought about making celebration cakes from home. But then an opportunity came along. \"I was asked to be an assistant food stylist on a recipe book. I turned up on the first day and didn't have a clue about publishing or how a photo shoot works. I had learned about styling food, but I had to work out how the different people involved fit in, but it didn't take long.\"</p><p>Which is just as well, because a change of circumstances meant Hudson was asked to style the shoot herself. \"It was a bit of a baptism of fire, but the publishers were very supportive and very encouraging. It was a bit of a do or die situation – I could either do this and really make a go of it or fail.\"</p><p>The job went well, and Hudson decided to go all out for a career as a food stylist. \"For most of the next year I did lots of assisting, because that is the way to learn. When you are assisting you help with the food prep, do all the washing up, and unpacking and packing up of food.</p><p>\"You are on standby for the stylist if they need something mid-photo, you make coffee for everyone, and act as a runner and help sweep the floor at the end of the day. You just watch everybody the whole time and soak it all up like a sponge. It's hard work, but a fantastic way to learn.\"</p><p>Her first book project gave Hudson the beginnings of a convincing portfolio, and the experience built up while assisting gave her more skills and brought her into contact with more people in the publishing industry. \"You meet a lot of people on the job, although you can't go in there with an agenda when you are assisting. I got a website set up early on so that I had something I could refer people to. But I am not a very pushy person; I tend to wait to be asked.\"</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-428862021'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/3/1391444802010/A-trifle-created-by-food--001.jpg' alt='A trifle created by food stylist Annie Hudson' width='220' height='278' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>A trifle created by food stylist Annie Hudson. Photograph: Myles New, from Lorraine Pascale's Home Cooking Made Easy</figcaption></figure><p>Before the end of her first year, Hudson was asked to be food stylist on another book, this time by Lorraine Pascale. \"That was another big break, and in the end I had three books under my belt in the first year at the same time as assisting and doing a bit of other work.\"</p><p>From then, the challenge has been to keep the momentum going, increasing her client base and making sure she is considered for projects. \"I found out the names of a few commissioning editors and sent them a link to my website so they have it on file. The key relationships are with the editors and photographers – they are very influential in how much work you get, and a lot depends on whether they are happy to work with you again.\"</p><p>Hudson has been working as a food stylist for four years and has never looked back. She can now add to her portfolio the food styling for books by Kirstie Allsopp, Fay Ripley and more. \"I've been very fortunate. I had a very lucky break, and of course not everyone has that. But at the same time you make your own luck, and I wouldn't have been given that opportunity if I had not equipped myself with the skills I have now.\"</p><p>Her skills as a trained chef are essential to the job – each recipe needs to be fully researched and all ingredients bought within a budget, and then made to perfection, ready to be photographed. You always choose the very best looking ingredients, and anything perishable has to be completely fresh on the day. But, she says, she never fakes the food for the sake of the picture. \"I might slightly undercook certain things, like green vegetables, so that they keep their shape or colour, but essentially everything would be edible.\"</p><p>She advises anyone considering a career in food styling to work very hard on gaining those crucial cookery skills, either by gaining experience in kitchens or catering, or by doing a cookery course. \"I have worked with assistants who say they want to do this job, and I say 'That's all very well but you've got to be able to cook'.</p><p>\"You have to have an artistic bent, but you must also be confident that you can work with most cooking methods and ingredients, and you have to know how to get yourself out of trouble if something doesn't work out.\"</p><p>With those skills under your belt, Hudson says, you can approach food stylists to offer your services as an assistant, and build up your experience from there. \"It is competitive, but if you work well as an assistant you will always be asked back. You will get recommended to other food stylists, publishers and photographers, and sometimes find that a generous stylist will put your name forward for a job if they are not available to do it themselves.\"</p>","headline":"How do I become … a food stylist","trailText":"<p>Preparing food, washing up, sweeping floors – start low but aim high and you might find yourself styling food for the big names</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mdg8","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/4/1391504994814/A-trifle-created-by-food--003.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Gu